","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","1290":"1290","1338":"1338","1325":"1325","after 1338":"after 1338","1323":"1323","1345":"1345","1400":"1400","1365":"1365","1254":"1254","1298":"1298","1319":"1319","Broxton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Broxton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Malpas, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Malpas St Chad, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Broxton, Cheshire, England":"Broxton, Cheshire, England","Haughton, Nantwich, Cheshire, England":"Haughton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bickerton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places (for example in Cheshire, Herefordshire, Northumberland, and Yorkshire) named Bickerton, from Old English <i>bīcere</i> ‘beekeeper’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</